## FORM HANDLING — REACT HOOK FORM + ZOD

Always use React Hook Form with Zod resolver. Never use uncontrolled forms
or manual `useState` per field for form data.

```typescript
// Zod schema in src/lib/validators.ts
export const saleSchema = z.object({
  date: z.string().min(1, 'Date required'),
  customerId: z.string().optional(),
  customerName: z.string().min(1, 'Customer name required'),
  items: z.array(saleItemSchema).min(1, 'At least one item required'),
  discount: z.number().int().min(0), // paise
  paymentMethod: z.enum(['cash', 'bank', 'upi', 'partial', 'credit']),
  bankAccountId: z.string().optional(),
  notes: z.string().optional(),
});

// In component
const form = useForm<SaleFormData>({
  resolver: zodResolver(saleSchema),
  defaultValues: { date: format(new Date(), 'yyyy-MM-dd'), items: [], discount: 0 }
});
```

MoneyInput component handles the paise↔rupees conversion internally:
```typescript
// User sees "1500.00", internal value is 150000 (paise)
<MoneyInput
  value={field.value}        // paise
  onChange={field.onChange}  // receives paise
  placeholder="0.00"
/>
```

---

## SEQUENCE NUMBERS (Auto-Numbering)

Sale numbers: `SALE-2024-001`, `SALE-2024-002`, ...
Purchase numbers: `PUR-2024-001`, ...
Expense numbers: `EXP-2024-001`, ...

Year in sequence is the financial year start year.
Counter resets to 001 every April 1st (FY start).
Counter stored in `settings` table in Dexie. Always increment atomically
inside a Dexie transaction.

```typescript
// src/lib/sequences.ts
export async function getNextSaleNumber(): Promise<string> {
  const settings = await db.settings.get('singleton');
  const fy = getCurrentFYYear(); // e.g., "2024"
  const next = (settings!.saleSequence || 0) + 1;
  await db.settings.update('singleton', { saleSequence: next });
  return `SALE-${fy}-${String(next).padStart(3, '0')}`;
}
```

---

## ERROR HANDLING PATTERNS

```typescript
// Async operations in components — always try/catch, always show toast
async function handleSubmit(data: FormData) {
  try {
    setLoading(true);
    await recordSale(data);
    toast.success('Sale recorded');
    navigate('/sales');
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('[handleSubmit]', err);
    toast.error(err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Something went wrong');
  } finally {
    setLoading(false);
  }
}

// Dexie queries — wrap in try/catch, return empty array on failure
async function getSales(start: string, end: string): Promise<Sale[]> {
  try {
    return await db.sales.where('date').between(start, end).toArray();
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('[getSales]', err);
    return [];
  }
}
```

Never swallow errors silently. Always log with a `[functionName]` prefix.

